1.  Introduction  
The following subsections of the Software Requirements Specifications (SRS) document provide an overview of the entire SRS. This document explicitly defines what the system must do so that designers can ultimately build it. 
1.1  Purpose  
This subsection describes the purpose of the particular SRS and specifies the intended audience. The purpose of this document is to define the functional and non-functional requirements for "Project Aether," a predictive, AI-driven hardware orchestrator. The intended audience includes the FYP supervisory committee, external university examiners, and the core development team. 
1.2  Scope 
Identify the software product: Project Aether.
What the software product will and will not do: The system will autonomously monitor hardware telemetry and use a Reinforcement Learning (RL) agent to adjust OS power plans and process affinities. It will not modify internal BIOS settings, flash firmware, or apply hardware-level overclocks.
Application and Objectives: The primary goal is to maximize foreground 3D application performance and mitigate thermal throttling without manual user intervention.

1.3  Definitions, Acronyms, and Abbreviations.  
This section provides the definitions of all terms, acronyms, and abbreviations required to properly interpret the SRS. 
RL (Reinforcement Learning): An AI paradigm where an agent learns to take actions to maximize a cumulative reward.
WMI (Windows Management Instrumentation): The infrastructure for management data and operations on Windows OS.
HAL (Hardware Abstraction Layer): A logical layer concealing physical hardware details from software.
Telemetry: The automatic recording of data from motherboard and processor sensors.

