2.  The Overall Description  
This section describes the general factors that affect the product and its requirements. It provides a background for the requirements defined in Section 3, making them easier to understand. 
2.1  Product Perspective  
Project Aether is independent and totally self-contained. It functions as a black box utility sitting between the active software applications and the host operating system's resource scheduler.

2.1.1 Operations
The software operates inside specific constraints.
1.	Normal Operations: The system operates in a passive, unattended mode in the system tray, consuming minimal CPU cycles to monitor baseline temperatures.
2.	Special Operations: An active orchestration mode triggers during the launch of heavy computational applications, shifting resource priorities.

2.1.2 Site Adaptation Requirements
The requirements for initialization sequences specific to a given site include the presence of a Windows 10/11 environment. Modern motherboard ACPI drivers must be installed prior to software activation to ensure valid telemetry polling. 
2.2  Product Functions 
This is a summary of the major functions that the software will perform.
1.	Real-Time Telemetry Acquisition: Granular tracking of CPU/GPU utilization and thermal states.
2.	Predictive Thermal Throttling Guard: Predicting heat-induced lag spikes prior to occurrence.
3.	Agentic Process Management: Algorithmic suppression of non-critical background processes.

2.3  User Characteristics 
This section describes the general characteristics of the intended users. The user base consists of PC gamers, developers, and power users who are comfortable with technology, which will drive a UI design that includes advanced data visualization.

2.4  General Constraints  
These are items that will limit the developer's options.
1.	Hardware limitations: The application must remain under 1.5% CPU utilization to prevent overhead.
2.	Control functions: Requires UAC Administrative privileges to modify process threads.
3.	Higher-order language requirements: Must be written entirely in Python 3.10+

2.5  Assumptions and Dependencies
These are factors that affect the requirements stated in the SRS. A primary assumption is that a specific operating system (64-bit Windows) will be available on the hardware designated for the software product. 
3.  Specific Requirements  
This is the largest and most important section, giving the D-requirements that guide the project's software design, implementation, and testing 


3.1  External Interface Requirements
3.1.1 System Interfaces
The system is self-contained and has no external corporate system interfaces requiring an API at this time 
3.1.2 Interfaces
This is a description of how the system will interact with its users. The system utilizes a GUI developed with CustomTkinter, providing real-time data visualization charts and toggle switches for performance profiles. 
3.1.3 Hardware Interfaces
This section specifies the logical characteristics between the software product and the hardware components. The system interfaces with CPU and GPU thermal registers and motherboard ACPI fans to read raw data arrays . 
3.1.4 Software Interfaces
This section specifies the use of other required software products.
1.	Name: Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI).
2.	Discussion: The system relies on WMI to fetch deep system metrics and execute OS-level process state manipulations.
3.	Other Libraries: Utilizes Python packages psutil, GPUtil, and Stable-Baselines3.

3.1.5 Communications Interfaces
The system has no local network protocol or communications interface requirements. 

3.2  Functional Requirements
3.2.1 Data Acquisition Engine 
3.2.1.1 Introduction: Gathers raw hardware data via sensor polling. 
3.2.1.2 Inputs: Raw integer arrays from CPU/GPU sensors.
3.2.1.3 Processing: Applies moving average filters to eliminate noise and mathematically normalizes data to a 0.0 - 1.0 scale.
3.2.1.4 Outputs: A structured Python dictionary sent to the AI Brain at 1000ms intervals. 
3.2.1.5 Error Handling: Falls back to the last known valid state vector if a sensor query timeouts.


3.2.2 AI Optimization Brain

3.2.2.1 Introduction: The core Reinforcement Learning decision module 
3.2.2.2 Inputs: The normalized state vector and target FPS constraint. 
3.2.2.3 Processing: A pre-trained PPO model evaluates the state to maximize rewards (high FPS, low thermals). 
3.2.2.4 Outputs: An action integer (e.g., Action 1: Change Power Plan).  
3.2.2.5 Error Handling: Defaults to native Windows scheduling if the AI confidence score drops. 

3.3  Use Cases
 

3.3.1 Use Case #1: Autonomous Game Optimization 
Upon detecting a heavy 3D executable, the system shifts into active mode, prioritizes the target .exe, and suppresses background sync tasks automatically. 

Field	Description
Use Case Name	Autonomous Game Optimization
Actor	System (Autonomous), Windows OS
Description	The system shifts into active orchestration mode upon detecting a heavy 3D application to prioritize performance.
Pre-conditions	Project Aether is running in the system tray; Windows 10/11 environment is active.
Post-conditions	Foreground process priority is increased; background sync tasks are suppressed.
Main Flow	1. System monitors active process list via WMI.
2. Heavy 3D executable is detected.
3. AI Brain evaluates current hardware state.
4. System shifts resource priorities and suppresses background tasks.
Alternative Flow	If AI confidence is low, the system defaults to native Windows scheduling.

3.3.2 Use Case #2: Predictive Thermal Mitigation 
The AI detects an upward velocity in hardware temperature. It predicts a throttle event in 15 seconds and preemptively lowers the CPU max power state to stabilize thermals. 
